Churn Anaysis -- Step2 Predict the Churn¶

This section will focus on the predictive modelings. The first step to understand the dataset can be found at: https://hehehe.shinyapps.io/Churn_Step1_/.

Before staring, a quick recall to previous analysis.

From the intutive visulization analysis, we knew that Contract, tenure and Total/Monthly Charges will effect Churn of customer. So here, we would like appling some classification models to validate and quantify the relationships between independent features and our Target(Churn).

Major Works were done¶

  • Data Clean and Preprocess

    • Clean data and features (remove outliers if any exists)
    • Onehot encoding for catagorical features
    • Scaling for numerical features

  • Build Models

    • Model1: Baseline Model(Logistic Regression)
    • Model2: Ridge Classifier
    • Model3: Gradient Boosting
    • Model4: Support Vector Classifier
    • Model5: Random Forest
    • Model6: XGboost (Go further)

  • Model Improvements

    • Model6: XGboost parameter tuning
    • Model6: XGboost weighted to improve F1 for final model

Key Conclusions¶

  • Baseline Model(Logistic Regression):
    • Accuracy : 79.18% |AUC Score: 71.01% |F1 Score : 57.84%
  • Other Models best one (XGboost tuned):
    • Accuracy : 80.24% |AUC Score: 72.07% |F1 Score : 59.59%
  • Final Model(XGboost weighted):
    • Accuracy : 78.89% |AUC Score: 73.52% |F1 Score : 61.07%

Consider about the business question, we should not only care about the accuracy of the model but also the Precision and Recall(Sensitivity).

- Precision: Of all the customers that we predicted as Churned, how many actually Churned?
- Recall(Sensitivity): Of all the customers that truly Churned, how many actually predicted as Churned?
- F1 score: F1 Score is the weighted average of Precision and Recall.

Here in this situation, the cost of false positive is lower than false negative. Which means that if a customer is actully churned, but the model predict it as Non-churned, it will be more harmful to the revenue than if a customer is actully Non-churned, but we predict it as Churned.

More Improvements¶

I belive that there are still a lot of things can be done, such as:

  • Get more data for modeling(only 7K in this dataset)
  • There are still lots of other popular classification models can be tried
  • Breakdown the dataset into different groups, for example, applied models on each contract group separately to see performance
  • Ensemble the weak classifications together to get better result

- Bucket tenure by year into 6 groups
- Bucket MonthlyCharges by quantile into 4 groups
- Bucket TotalCharges by quantile into 4 groups
In [5]:

data["TotalCharges"] = data["TotalCharges"].astype(float)
#data['Total'] = pd.to_numeric(data['TotalCharges'], errors='coerce')

#Create numeric bucket
#1. tenure_group
def tenure_group_fun(x):
    if x['tenure'] <= 12:
        return 'tenure_group1'  
    if x['tenure'] <= 24:
        return 'tenure_group2'
    if x['tenure'] <= 36:
        return 'tenure_group2' 
    if x['tenure'] <= 48:
        return 'tenure_group3'
    if x['tenure'] <= 60:
        return 'tenure_group4'  
    if x['tenure'] <= 72:
        return 'tenure_group5'
    
data['tenure_group'] = data.apply(tenure_group_fun, axis = 1)

#2. MonthlyCharge cut by quantile into 4 group
bin_labels = ['monthly_Q1', 'monthly_Q2', 'monthly_Q3', 'monthly_Q4']
data['monthly_group'] = pd.qcut(data['MonthlyCharges'], q=[0, .25, .5, .75, 1], labels=bin_labels)

#3. TotalCharge cut by quantile into 4 group
bin_labels = ['total_Q1', 'total_Q2', 'total_Q3', 'total_Q4']
data['total_group'] = pd.qcut(data['TotalCharges'], q=[0, .25, .5, .75, 1], labels=bin_labels)

#For mutiple features, create dummies varibles
#One-hot encode and combine, drop the original feature and clean the value

def encode_and_bind(input_dataframe, feature_to_encode):
    #Create the dummies for given feature
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(input_dataframe[[feature_to_encode]])
    #Concat the dummies features
    res = pd.concat([input_dataframe, dummies], axis=1)
    #Drop the original one
    res = res.drop([feature_to_encode], axis=1)
    return(res) 

for feature in cat_mul_cols:
    data = encode_and_bind(data, feature)
    
#Removing specical charachter '- ()' in column names
data.columns = data.columns.str.replace(r'[- ()]+','_')

Try IQR to remove the outliers if any.¶

In [14]:
def subset_by_iqr(df, column, whisker_width=1.5):
    """Remove outliers from a dataframe by column, including optional 
       whiskers, removing rows for which the column value are 
       less than Q1-1.5IQR or greater than Q3+1.5IQR.
    Args:
        df (`:obj:pd.DataFrame`): A pandas dataframe to subset
        column (str): Name of the column to calculate the subset from.
        whisker_width (float): Optional, loosen the IQR filter by a
                               factor of `whisker_width` * IQR.
    Returns:
        (`:obj:pd.DataFrame`): Filtered dataframe
    """
    # Calculate Q1, Q2 and IQR
    q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)                 
    q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    # Apply filter with respect to IQR, including optional whiskers
    filter = (df[column] >= q1 - whisker_width*iqr) & (df[column] <= q3 + whisker_width*iqr)
    return df.loc[filter]                                                     

data_filtered = subset_by_iqr(data, 'TotalCharges', whisker_width=1.5)
data_filtered = subset_by_iqr(data_filtered, 'MonthlyCharges', whisker_width=1.5)

3.4 Report the learning curve(to see whether there are any overfittings)¶

In [150]:
#Report the learning curve 
def plot_learning_curve(estimator, title, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None, n_jobs=1, 
                        train_sizes=np.linspace(.05, 1., 20), verbose=0, plot=True):
    """
    Plot learning curve of applied data model.
    ----------
    estimator : Classification
    title : title of plot
    X : features in numpy
    y : tearget in matrix
    ylim : tuple with (ymin, ymax)
    cv : cross-validation fold default as 3
    n_jobs : 
    """
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
        estimator, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes, verbose=verbose)
    
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    
    if plot:
        plt.figure()
        plt.title(title)
        if ylim is not None:
            plt.ylim(*ylim)
        plt.xlabel(u"Training examples")
        plt.ylabel(u"Score")
        plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
        plt.grid()
    
        plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std, train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, 
                         alpha=0.1, color="b")
        plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std, test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, 
                         alpha=0.1, color="r")
        plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="b", label=u"Training score")
        plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r", label=u"Cross-validation score")
    
        plt.legend(loc="best")
        
        plt.draw()
        plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
        plt.show()
    
    midpoint = ((train_scores_mean[-1] + train_scores_std[-1]) + (test_scores_mean[-1] - test_scores_std[-1])) / 2
    diff = (train_scores_mean[-1] + train_scores_std[-1]) - (test_scores_mean[-1] - test_scores_std[-1])
    return midpoint, diff

#plot_learning_curve(clf_under, u"leraning curve", X, y)
plot_learning_curve(model1, u"Learning curve of Baseline Model (Logistic Regression)", X_train, y_train, ylim = [0.5,1])

Model in Reality¶

Consider about the business question, we should not only care about the accuracy of the model but also the Precision and Recall(Sensitivity).

  • Precision: Of all the customers that we predicted as Churned, how many actually Churned?
  • Recall(Sensitivity): Of all the customers that truly Churned, how many actually predicted as Churned?
  • F1 score: F1 Score is the weighted average of Precision and Recall.

Here in this situation, the cost of false positive is lower than false negative. Which means that if a customer is actully churned, but the model predict it as Non-churned, it will be more harmful to the revenue than if a customer is actully Non-churned, but we predict it as Churned.

XGboost weighted¶

The mian idea here is to add more weight for Churn in the loss function try to improve the F1 score
